body.text: This is experimental code by a hobbyist to combine the real time parking availability data of SFPark with the simple but powerful TouchDevelop environment to create real time parking availability maps on your phone.
Oh, hello! I didn't see you there.  I normally just work on my code in private, just me and the compiler. Had I known you were coming I would have cleaned the place up a bit.

What the heck are all these user inputs doing here?  Well, see here's the thing, I am trying to track down a pesky little big and you caught me right in the middle of it.  As best as I can figure out, TouchDevelop is multithreaded and sets of some asynchronous tasks for web responses, map drawing,and the like.
The problem seems to be that when the asynchronous task tries to continue, it finds that the continuation task is disposed or hasn't waited for the async task completion.
(Of course, if I actually knew what I was talking about I would be programming in visual studio, not scripting on my HD7.)

These user inputs are for two purposes: 1) they clearly illustrate that there is some sort of bug since the UI thread just blows through the request for user input 2) they apparently slow down a thread enough so that when the asynchronous thread completes, it has somewhere to go, rather than throwing an exception.
